  array (
    'en_US' => '<h1>&nbsp;Scope and Editorial Policy of the Journal</h1>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p>The journal <em>Ingeniería y Competitividad </em>is a scientific and technological publication which aims to disseminate advances in engineering. It publishes papers from all engineering branches, and related sciences. Multidisciplinary, scientific, and technical articles with substantial high quality content are welcome. The journal also publishes original articles in applied sciences that describe new and significant developments which are applicable in solving engineering problems. The journal has national and international impact. It is published twice a year.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The contents, concepts, and opinions of the articles are solely the responsibility of the author(s), and cannot in any case be&nbsp;considered as reflecting the opinion or policies of the journal, the Engineering School nor the Editorial Committee of Universidad del Valle.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The author(s) must guarantee that submitted articles have not been published elsewhere; by any means whether printed, electronic or digital media. This includes other journals, congresses memories, web pages, CD-ROMs, etc. Additionally, authors must guarantee that the articles are not currently under review elsewhere. Submitting the same article to more than one journal concurrently constitutes an unethical publishing behavior and is unacceptable. The author(s) must write a letter with the submission certifying that the article is original and unpublished, and that the submission is exclusively for the Journal of<em> Ingenieria y Competividad</em>. The journal will use available tools to avoid any inappropriate use of information or plagiarism of published works. This action will be subject to severe sanctions, in accordance to the ethical commitments of the authors.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The articles are accepted for publication based on a rigorous review process of its academic quality. The author(s) must be explicit about the scope of&nbsp; his/theirwork; the objective is to carry out the research as well as the results, and a rigorous, technical and scientific analysis.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The article must have all details, references, and cites to allow other people to replicate the work. The author(s) must cite the publications that have influenced them while developing their own work. Fraudulent or intentionally inexact statements constitute an unethical publishing behavior and is unacceptable.</p>
<p>The articles can be written in Spanish, English, and Portuguese. Articles are accepted according to the general criteria established for scientific journal of engineering, some of which are:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Articles of scientific or technological research</strong>: They present original results from a research. Papers must include five sections: 1. Introduction, 2. Methodology, 3. Results and discussion, 4. Conclusions, 5. References.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Articles of Reflection</strong>: They present research results regarding a specific issue from the authors’ analytical, interpretative, or critical perspective, citing original bibliographic sources.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Review Articles</strong>: They present the result of an analytical review of the literature about a specific issue, systematizing or integrating the results of published researches in order to inform the advances, and development trends on the issue as well. They include a wide and careful bibliographic review.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Short Articles</strong>: They present preliminary or partial results of a research which requires a fast diffusion and are likely to be published according to their degree of innovation, and importance in technical and scientific aspects.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Case Reports</strong>: These works only present technical and methodological experiences associated to a specific case study. They are relevant due to their innovation and novelty.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Guidelines for Authors</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Presentation of the articles</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Articles can be written in Spanish, English or Portuguese. They must be free of spelling and grammatical errors.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Articles should not exceed 20 pages, including tables and figures.They must be written in double-spaced, 216mm X 279mm paper, 12 point font in a single column.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Submitting files</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>The work will submitted by using an OJS platform or its equivalent. The author shall refrain from submitting articles to the editor or the journal’s email.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The files that must be enclosed are:</p>
<p>&nbsp;The article in a Word format</p>
<p>&nbsp;A letter addressed to the Managing Editor certifying that the submitted article complies all requirements of the guidelines for authors. The letter must also certify the originality and novelty of the work, and the exclusivity of its submission to the journal <em>Ingenieria y&nbsp;</em><em>Competividad</em>.&nbsp; It must authorize the journal to put the work under the consideration of the evaluators appointed by the Editor-in-Chief. Likewise, the authors pledge not to remove the article or submit it to another journal without being notified by the Editorial Board stating that the article has not been admitted for publication. This letter must also include the full title of the work, the engineering area related to the topic covered in the work, as well as the authors’ names, surnames, their institutional e-mail, their academic degrees, and positions in the institution. They should also suggest at least three (3) evaluators, and the names of the institutions they belong to, and their e-mails. The journal has the power to use these evaluators in order to evaluate the submission or other received articles. This letter must be signed by all authors involved in the work.</p>
<p>The original files of each image or any type of graph included in the article in jpg or tiff format should have at least a 300 dpi resolution.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The original files of each table must be in Excel format.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Structure of the Article</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;The entire text of the article, including table headers, figure foot notes, and bibliographical references, must be written using Time New Romans font (TNR). The entire text of the article should be at line numbered (this is done by using the Page Layout option-line numbering). This is to facilitate the Editorial Committee members and the evaluators to read and make notes of the corrections, as well as the correction done by the authors in the final stages of the process. The article must have the following structure and comply with the following requirements:</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Title</strong>: It should clearly, precisely, and concisely represent the content of the article. Acronyms or abbreviations should be avoided whenever possible. There should be a version of the title in English if the article has been written in Spanish or Portuguese. If the title is written in English or Portuguese, a version in Spanish should be included. The title should be centered between the margins, written in TNR bold font, size 18, and double spaced.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Authors</strong>. Authors should clearly indicate their given name(s), the first letter of their middle name (if any), and the family name(s) of each author in this order. All names must be checked for accurately spelling. If the author(s) is/are used to writing two family names in the literature, they should be linked by a hyphen. In order to better visualize the authors names, it is recommended to sign all the works with a unique bibliographical name which identifies the author(s) in the entire article. Other information following the list of authors should be separated by commas, written in TNR bold font, size 12, and double spaced.Principio del formulario</p>
<p>Symbols, such as simple asterisk, double asterisk, etc., must be used and inserted as superscripts at the end of the family name of each author to indicate his/their membership afterwards. One of the authors should be identified as the corresponding author using the symbol § placed as a second superscript at the end of his/her surname. This author will handle correspondence with the Editor-in-Chief, and is the author who the readers of the journal must address their comments and inquisitiveness to.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Affiliations</strong>. The name of the institution to which each the author is affiliated should be specified. In the case of authors affiliated to universities, the name the academic unit, school or department should be followed by the name of the university, city and country. In the case of authors affiliated to companies, the name of the department should be written first, then the section or division followed by the company’s name, city and country. Affiliation are listed preceded by the symbol that was inserted as the superscript after each author’s surname, and should be written in TNR, italics, size 11, and double spaced. Author(s) academic degrees and work positions should not be included. The corresponding author’s e-mail address should be written preceded by the symbol §, and also the e-mail address of each co-author in the same order they appear.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Summary</strong>: The summary must establish the scope and aim of the work, providing a clear and concise description of the methodology, main results, and obtained conclusions. It should be maximum 300 words in extension and should be headed by the word summary written in bold TNR font, size 12. The summary text should be written in TNR font, size 10.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Keywords</strong>: A maximum of 5 keywords must be chosen. These are listed preceded by the label Keywords: written in TNR font, bold, italics, and size 10. The consecutive elements in the keywords list should be separated by commas, beginning with a capital letter written in TNR fond, size 10. Each element in the keyword list may have maximum 4 words including prepositions.Final del formulario</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Abstract: </strong>It should be a correct and precise translation to English of the text in the summary written in Spanish. Authors who do not have a good command of English should properly look for advice to ensure that the translation is of the highest possible quality. The same editing style specified for the summary in Spanish should be used.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Keywords</strong>: <strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Keywords should be a correct and precise translation to English of the keywords list in Spanish. Authors who do not have a good command of English should properly look for advice to ensure that the translation is of the highest possible quality. The same editing style specified for the keywords in Spanish should be used.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Main Text</strong>: For articles on scientific and technological research, the main body of the work must be composed of five sections: 1. Introduction, 2. Methodology, 3. Results and discussion, 4.Conclusions, 5. Bibliographical References. If it is the case, an additional section for acknowledgements can be included. A title for each section must be included with the corresponding Arabic numeral (1, 2, 3, 4 or 5). The numeral and number in each section should be written in bold, TNR font, size 12. If it is necessary to use subtitles in each section, they should be written in bold, TNR font, size 11. The text in each section should be written in TNR font, size 11. The text should be written in a single column, &nbsp;2.5&nbsp; cm margins on both sides, and double-spaced. The usage of footnotes for making annotations to the main text is not permitted.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Equations</strong>: They must be centered with respect to the main text. Consecutive Arabic numerals, written in parenthesis closed to the right margin, should be used to label equations, which are cited in the main text using the abbreviated equation word Eq., and followed by the Arabic numeral in parentheses. If possible, a uniform format should be used for all the equations in the article, writing the variables in italics, the subscript and superscript of variables in normal type, and vectors and matrices in bold. A horizontal bar must be used to indicate division in the main terms of an equation, and a slash to indicate the division in the 3/2 exponents of powers (for example, q<sup>3 / 2</sup>). The meaning and units to be used for all variables or symbols in the equations must be written immediately after the equation where they were used for the first time. Alternatively, the variables or symbols can be compiled in a nomenclature section, which provides both the definition of each one of the variables (or symbols), alphabetically sorted as the units to be used. This section must be placed after the conclusions section (or the acknowledgments).</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Quantities</strong>: For all the numeric quantities reported in the main text of the work, and in the equations, tables and figures, a comma should be used to separate thousands, and a point should be used to indicate the decimal numbers.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Bibliographical</strong> <strong>References</strong>:</p>
<p>&nbsp;Within the body of the article, the&nbsp; Vancouver citation system should be used.&nbsp; &nbsp;See references Vancouver states that documents, ideas or literal fragments of other authors are cited within the text, without separated notes, and that a list of cited references is included at the end of the paper. The citations are inserted by numbers in parentheses in consecutive order, in order of mention (in case of mentioning the same citations for the second time, the number given to the cited will be used the first time). If the authors are more than two, it is abbreviated et al. (and others). For example: "... since the association between sudden death and sport has been and is controversial (1). There is not enough evidence and there is controversy about the impact on the patient and the clinical outcome (2-5,8). The higher incidence of abnormal findings in our study compared to Jiménez et al. (9) responds to ... In chronic patients without heart disease, a recent study (12) has clearly shown ... This data is consistent with the only series published in Italy in this regard (14), in which ... ... but in certain studies it has been also observed a lower in-hospital mortality (9,13,18). Alberts (13.15), Hastings and Smith (17) and Dahlen (21) studied its effect, but their conclusions did not coincide.&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;The list of bibliographical references should be written at the end of the text of the article, after the conclusions section. Authors should carefully verify that all citations in the text of the article are in the bibliographical reference list. Only the bibliographical references that were cited in the main text of the article, in tables, and figures should be included in the list.That is, other references consulted by the authors to prepare the articles should not be included in the list. The text within each reference should be written in TNR font, and size 11.&nbsp; References are included numerically. Only Arabic numbers are used and titles can be abbreviated. Only the first word of the title should be capitalized. The title of the works is cited in its original language. The order to reference names is: last name followed by the initial of the name, without points. When there are no personal or corporate authors, the title is put first. If the document is on the Internet, the citation date and the location on the network are indicated. For documents with DOI, the DOI address is used as location.</p>
<p>&nbsp;If you only have an approximate publication date, use c (circa), eg: c1998. Abbreviate the months to the first 3 letters. When it is appropriate to abbreviate the page numbers (Ej: p. 122-8)</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Format for reference articles in journals:</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Castle M, Nájera E, Samprón N, Bollar A, Urreta I, Úrculo E. Stereotactic brain biopsy without frame: diagnostic capacity and complications. Neurosurgery. 2014 mar;25(2):56-61.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Jutel M, Jaeger L, Suck R et al. Allergen-specific immunotherapy with recombinant grass pollen allergens. J Allergy Clin Immunol [Internet]. 2005 sep [aforementioned</p>
<p>&nbsp;10 sep 2014]; 116(3):608-13. Avalaible in: <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jaci.2005.06.004">http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jaci.2005.06.004</a></p>
<p>If there are more than 6 authors, after the first 6 et al is used. The names of the journals should be abbreviated. The months are abbreviated to the first three letters (without period). The volume followed by the number in parentheses is indicated. The page numbers are abbreviated when possible (Ex: 123-29). DOI of the journal should be provided whenever possible.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Format for reference books</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;Fletcher RH, Fletcher SW. Clinical epidemiology. 4ª ed. Barcelona: Wolters Kluwer Health España; 2008. 269 p.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Reidhaar-Olson JF, Rondinone CM, editors. Therapeutic Applications of RNAi: Methods and Protocols [Internet]. New York: Humana Press; 2009 [aforementioned 10 sep 2014]. 144 p. Available in: <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-1-60327-295-7">http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-1-60327-295-7</a></p>
<p>All names of the authors are given, separated by comma and space and in the order in which they appear in the book. For digital books include the DOI (if available) and the URL.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Format for reference chapters in books:</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Meltzer PS, Kallioniemi A, Trent JM. Chromosome alterations in human solid tumors. In: Vogelstein B, Kinzler KW, editors. The genetic basis of human cancer. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2002. p. 93-113.</p>
<p>For book chapters, these are abbreviated with page numbers (Ex: p.12-25). The title of the chapter must be provided after the names of the authors. Then use \'En:\' followed by the names of the editors. Follow the title of the book, the number of the edition (in case it is not the first edition) and the place of publication, publisher, year of publication and pages.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Format for reference papers in congresses:</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;Moreno-Alemán J. The prescription of medicines and health products by the nursing staff. In: Adroher Biosca S et al., coordinators. International Congress The advances of the Law before the advances of Medicine; 2008; Madrid. Cizur Menor (Navarra): Aranzadi; 2008. p. 283-300.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Format for reference jobs available via the Internet:</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Carlos III Health Institute [Internet]. Madrid: ISCIII; c2014. National Registry of Biobanks;</p>
<p>&nbsp;[aforementioned 10 sep 2014]. [1 pantalla]. Avalaible in: <a href="http://www.isciii.es/ISCIII/es/contenidos/fd-servicios-cientifico-tecnicos/registro-nacional-de-Biobancos-2.shtml">http://www.isciii.es/ISCIII/es/contenidos/fd-servicios-cientifico-tecnicos/registro-nacional-de-Biobancos-2.shtml</a></p>
<p>All names of authors must be included in the order in which they appear on the page. Use the title of the main page of the website. After the title include the word Internet in brackets \'[Internet]\'. The publication site is the city where the main page is published (if you do not know how to use \'[Unknown place]\'). The publisher is the person or organization that publishes the page. For dates use the date on which the page was first published, always include the year. Also include the last update date (Year / Month) and the date on which the site was consulted. Use the phrase "Available in:" followed by the URL.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Format for referencing degree theses:</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Borkowski MM. Infant sleep and feeding: a telephone survey of Hispanic Americans [dissertation]. Mount Pleasant (MI): Central Michigan University; 2002.</p>
<p>Castañeda Fernández M. Study of the microsatellites and miniSTRos of the X chromosome of forensic application [doctoral thesis on the Internet]. Santander: &nbsp;Universidad de Cantabria; 2013 [aforementioned 10 sep 2014]. 172 p. available in: <a href="http://hdl.handle.net/10902/3053">http://hdl.handle.net/10902/3053</a></p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Format to reference reports or technical documents:</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Russell ML, Goth-Goldstein R, Apte MG, Fisk WJ. Method for measuring the size distribution of airborne Rhinovirus. Berkeley (CA): Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Environmental Energy Technologies Division; 2002 Jan. Report No.: LBNL49574. Contract No.: DEAC0376SF00098. Sponsored by the Department of Energy.</p>
<p>Include the names of all the authors. If the author is an organization, provide the full name of the organization followed by the country of the organization in parentheses summarized with the two letters of the country code (Ex: (CO) for a Colombian organization). If both are cited, prefer the name of the author. If there are no authors, only editors, write the name of all the editors separated by comma and space followed by the word "editors". The place of publication is the city where the report was published. If it is American or Canadian cities, follow the name of the city by the two-letter state code (EJ: NY for the state of New York). For electronic reports include the DOI after the URL.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Tables. </strong>Tables should be included within the main text of the paper, arranged in the same order citation followed in the main text. The header of each table should include the word <em>Table</em> (in italics) followed by consecutive, corresponding, Arabic numerals, and a brief description of table content. The header must be written with TNR font, in italics and size 9. The columns in the table should have headers. Only horizontal lines should be used to separate entries in it. Vertical lines should not be used to separate its columns. In case a footnote is required, it must be written in TNR font, and size 8. Tables should not duplicate the information given in the figures.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Illustrations. </strong>Figures (or photographs) should be included within the main text according to the citation order in the main text. Each label should include the word <em>Figure</em> (in italics) followed by the corresponding, consecutive, Arabic numerals, and a brief description of the figure content. The figure caption should be written in italics, TNR font, and size 9. Figures should be printed in black and white. As illustrations are not accepted in color, the use of different types of symbols or lines in the graphs which use Cartesian coordinate, should be made; and grayscale color in pie graphs and photographs should be done as well. Labels in all figures must be written in a size that is legible when the figure is reduced to fit in the width of a column during the layout process. Figures should be included as original imported images or copied to the work file from a graphical tool (for example, Microsoft Excel) with a sufficiently high resolution, so that readability is kept when the figure size is adjusted during the editing process.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Submission checklist</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>The following list will be useful during the final checking of an article prior to submitting it to the journal for review. Make sure all guidelines are followed, otherwise the works or articles may be rejected.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Authors must certify the originality and novelty of the work in a letter. It must also certify the submission exclusivity to the journal of <em>Ingeniería y Competitividad.</em></p>
<p>&nbsp;The submitted article should be in a Microsoft Word or WordPerfect format, not exceeding 20 pages including tables and figures, double-spaced, letter-size paper, 12-point font in a single column.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The article meets bibliographic requirements outlined in the Author’s Guidelines, and uses the</p>
<p>reference system citation Harvard: http://libweb.anglia.ac.uk/referencing/files/Harvard_referencing_</p>
