<p>&nbsp;<strong>Eva</strong><strong>luation Process</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;The acceptance of an article for publication is based on a rigorous evaluation process, and its academic and scientific quality.&nbsp;The double-blind evaluation process guarantees the anonymity of authors and reviewers, the majority are external to the publishing institution.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The Editor-in-Chief, in association with the member of the Editorial Committee associated to the corresponding area of the submitted work, makes the first evaluation to verify if it complies with the presentation rules, and its relation with the journal’s scope; after this, the work is rejected or accepted to continue with the peer evaluation.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Articles are submitted to two expert evaluators in the respective areas of knowledge, which are nominated by the Editorial Committee. The evaluators take about one or two months to submit a detailed concept on the organization and writing of the article, its originality and the scope of the presented work, the approach and justification of the addressed problem, the description of the used methodology, the presentation and discussion of results, consistency between the results and conclusions, and the relevance and accuracy of the cited bibliographical references.</p>
<p>&nbsp;After receiving the peers’ evaluations, and based on their recommendations, the Editor-in-Chief makes the decision to accept or reject the article. If there are different concepts of the article, the assessment of a third reviewer will be sought. If the paper is rejected, it will be returned to the author(s) along with the evaluators’ comments, and the recommendation to correct the work, and to consider its publication in another journal. The decision to reject a work is a final decision, and it is not subjected to appeal. If the work is accepted with the recommendation to make whether minor or great changes, this, together with the evaluators’ comments, is returned to the authors for them to prepare a revised and corrected version to be submitted one month later. Authors must submit the corrected version along with a letter addressed to the Editor-in-Chief, listing in detail, the implemented changes in accordance with the recommendations made by the evaluators. The Editor-in-Chief takes the final decision regarding the acceptance of the corrected version considering the concept of the evaluators, and the corrections made by the authors.</p>
